Why?

Because now we have to take
ALL those individual sorted modules
and wire them back together
into ONE working system.

That means:

1. __init__.py files
   Every directory needs one.
   Each one needs the RIGHT imports.
   Wrong imports = broken mesh.

2. Import resolution
   Module A needs Module B.
   Module B needs Module C.
   What order do we wire them?
   Circular imports = dead system.

3. C++ namespaces + CMake
   Headers need include guards.
   Source files need namespace blocks.
   CMakeLists.txt needs every target.

4. The mesh entry point
   One file that wires ALL rooms.
   The sovereign __init__.py
   at the top of everything.

5. Room-to-room connections
   room-2 might depend on room-0.
   How do we detect that?
   How do we wire it safely?
We solve it in layers.
Each layer solves ONE problem.

LAYER 1 — Directory __init__.py
  Walk every sorted directory.
  Generate __init__.py for each.
  Import only what's in that folder.
  No guessing. No globals.

LAYER 2 — Dependency graph
  Read every manifest.json
  from the split phase.
  Build a directed graph:
    validate → process → engine
  Sort it topologically.
  Wire in safe order.
  Detect cycles before they break.

LAYER 3 — Room package
  Each room becomes a package:
    room-2/
      __init__.py   ← exports everything
      core/
        __init__.py
        process.py
      validation/
        __init__.py
        validate.py

LAYER 4 — Mesh entry point
  integration/output/mesh/
    __init__.py     ← imports all rooms
    room_0/
    room_2/
    room_3/

LAYER 5 — C++ targets (if needed)
  CMakeLists.txt per room
  + master CMakeLists.txt
  that add_subdirectory() all rooms

LAYER 6 — Integration manifest
  Full map of everything wired.
  What depends on what.
  What version each room is.
  Proof the mesh is solid.
